RT  Urocanase and N-formimino-L-glutamate formiminohydrolase of Bacillus
RT  subtilis, two enzymes of the histidine degradation pathway.
RA  Kaminskas E, Kimhi Y, Magasanik B;
RL  J Biol Chem. 1970;245:3536-3544.
DC  Histidine Catabolism
DR  IUBMB; AminoAcid; His3;
DC  Histidine Metabolism
DR  KEGG; map00340;
CC  This pathway is involved in histidine utilization system (hut). HutP is
CC  the first gene in the hut operon encoding the hutHUIG operator and a
CC  positive regulator of the operon, activated allostatically in the
CC  presence of L-histidine. HutC represses the histidine utilization by
CC  binding the regulatory sites for the hutHUIG and hutF the divergent.In
CC  some species, histidine is converted to via urocanate and then
CC  formimino-L-glutamate to glutamate in four steps, where the fourth step
CC  is conversion of N-formimino-L-glutamate to L-glutamate and formamide.
CC  In others, that pathway from formimino-L-glutamate have two other
CC  possible alternatives. One is involved with the tetrahydrofolate (THF)
CC  dependent glutamate formiminotransferase interconverting L-glutamate
CC  and N-formimino-L-glutamate. The enzyme is bifunctional as it also
CC  catalyzes the cyclodeaminase reaction on N-formimino-THF, converting it
CC  to 5,10-methenyl-THF and releasing ammonia - part of the process of
CC  regenerating THF. The other alternative is involved with hutF
CC  (formiminoglutamate hydrolase).
**  from group 20027
